THOUGHT

I inspected `polymorph.c` and reproduced the provided `-f` crash. The ASan-instrumented binary actually aborts first in `grok_commandLine()` at `polymorph.c:118` because `strcpy(target, optarg)` overflows the global `target[MAX]` when the command-line filename is at least 2048 bytes plus NUL. That prevents this exact binary/run from reaching `convert_fileName()`. To isolate the described `convert_fileName()` defect, I built a small harness that calls `convert_fileName()` directly with a 2050-byte uppercase string; ASan reports a stack-buffer-overflow on `newname` at `polymorph.c:193`, in the loop at lines 191-198. Thus there are multiple manifestations of the same underlying design flaw: raw fixed-size filename buffers and unbounded copies/transforms.

ROOT CAUSE: `polymorph.c:191-198` in `convert_fileName()` writes `newname[i]` for every byte in `original` and then writes `newname[i] = '\0'`, but `newname` is only `char newname[MAX]` where `MAX == 2048` (`polymorph_types.h:9`). If `strlen(original) >= 2048`, the loop and/or terminator write past the end of the stack buffer, corrupting the stack and potentially the saved return address. The normal `./polymorph -f <long>` path also has an earlier unbounded copy at `polymorph.c:118` (`strcpy(target, optarg)`) into a 2048-byte global buffer, so the supplied repro is stopped there by ASan before reaching the stack overflow. Other unsafe copies exist too (`strcpy(filename, victim->d_name)`, `strcpy(newname, original)`, `strcpy(original, newname)`), showing that the invariant “all filenames fit in MAX” is neither checked nor encoded.

LOCAL FIX: Reject or safely bound filenames before copying/converting, and make `convert_fileName()` guarantee room for the terminator. A minimal repair is:

```diff
--- a/polymorph.c
+++ b/polymorph.c
@@ -117,7 +117,12 @@ void grok_commandLine(int argc, char *argv[]){
-      strcpy( target, optarg );
+      if (strlen(optarg) >= sizeof target) {
+        fprintf(stderr, "filename too long (max %zu bytes)\n",
+                sizeof target - 1);
+        exit(1);
+      }
+      strcpy(target, optarg);
       break;
@@ -188,14 +193,21 @@ void convert_fileName(char *original){
-  if( does_nameHaveUppers( original ) ){
+  size_t len = strlen(original);
+  if (len >= sizeof newname) {
+    fprintf(stderr, "filename too long (max %zu bytes): %s\n",
+            sizeof newname - 1, original);
+    return;
+  }
+
+  if( does_nameHaveUppers( original ) ){
     /* convert the filename */
-    for(i=0;i<strlen(original);i++){
+    for(i=0; original[i] != '\0'; i++){
       if( isupper( original[i] ) ){
-        newname[i] = tolower( original[i] );
+        newname[i] = (char)tolower((unsigned char)original[i]);
         continue;
       }
       newname[i] = original[i];
     }
     newname[i] = '\0';
   }else{
-    strcpy( newname, original );
+    memcpy(newname, original, len + 1);
     error = -1;
   }
```

For a complete local hardening pass, the same length check or bounded copy must be applied to the other `strcpy()` calls that write into fixed arrays (`filename`, `wd`, `target`, `newname`, and any caller-provided `original` buffer).

GLOBAL FIX: Redesign filename handling so conversion functions do not accept or return unconstrained mutable C strings backed by arbitrary fixed arrays. Introduce a single filename abstraction/API that carries capacity and length, e.g. `struct filename { char *buf; size_t len; size_t cap; }`, or use dynamically allocated strings where `convert_fileName(const char *original, char **converted)` allocates exactly `strlen(original)+1` bytes after validating against filesystem limits (`NAME_MAX`/`PATH_MAX` as appropriate). Centralize all copies/transforms through checked helpers such as `filename_set()` and `filename_lowercase()` that return errors on overflow. This removes duplicated `MAX` assumptions and makes it impossible for callers like command-line parsing and directory traversal to bypass bounds checks. Keep ASan/UBSan and compiler warnings enabled in CI, and add boundary tests at lengths `MAX-1`, `MAX`, and `MAX+1`.

